{"title_page": "Tissa Weeratunga", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Tissa Indraka Weeratunga\n|birth_date=August 29, 1930\n|death_date=November 2003\n|birth_place= [[Matara, Sri Lanka|Matara]], [[Ceylon]]\n|death_place= [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]]\n|image=<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:General Tissa Weeratunga.jpg|250px]] -->\n|caption= General Tissa Weeratunga\n|nickname= Bull\n|allegiance= [[Sri Lanka]]\n|serviceyears= 1951-1986\n|rank=[[General]] \n|branch=[[Sri Lanka Army]]\n|commands=[[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|Chief of the Defence Staff]],<br>[[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]],<br> [[Chief of Staff]] of the Sri Lankan Army \n|unit=<!-- Commented out: [[File:SLLI Crest.gif|25px]] -->[[Ceylon Light Infantry]],<br>[[Gemunu Watch]]\n|battles= [[1971 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|1971 Insurrection]], <br>[[Sri Lankan Civil War]]\n|awards=[[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya]]\n|laterwork= [[High Commissioner (Commonwealth)|High Commissioner]] to [[Canada]]\n}}\n\n[[General (Sri Lanka)|General]] '''Tissa Indraka Weeratunga''', [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya|VSV]], [[National Defence College, India|ndc]], [[psc (British Army)|psc]], [[Gemunu Watch|GW]] (August 29, 1930 &ndash; November 2003) was a [[Sri Lanka]] [[general]]. He was a former [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]] (1981 \u2013 1985) and first [[General Officer Commanding]] (GOC) of the Joint Operations Headquarters (JOH) (at present referred [[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|Chief of the Defence Staff]]), he was later Sri Lanka's [[High Commissioner (Commonwealth)|High Commissioner]] to Canada.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn to Arthur Weeratunga, [[Plantation|planter]] from [[Matara, Sri Lanka|Matara]] and Henrietta Weeratunga ([[n\u00e9e]] Gurusingha). He had one sister, Krishnajina who married [[Ana Seneviratne]] (former Sri Lankan Inspector-General of Police). Tissa Weeratunga was educated at the [[Royal College, Colombo]]. He was a graduate of the [[Joint Service Defence College]] and the [[National Defence College, India]].<ref name=\"GW1\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20150618042042/http://www.gemunuesra.lk/general_bull_weeratunga_remembered.html GENERAL TI WEERATHUNGA VSV ndc jssc (Retd) REMEMBERED]</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n===Early career===\nWeeratunga joined the newly formed Ceylon Army on 11 October 1949, in its first cadet officer intake and received his basic officer training at Mons Officer Cadet School, Aldershot and at [[Royal Military Academy, Sandhurst]], and was commissioned as a [[Second Lieutenant]] and posted to the [[Ceylon Light Infantry]] on 2 August 1951. He was appointed as [[adjutant]] of the [[Ruhunu Regiment]] on 4 July 1956; adjutant of the 1 Battalion, Ceylon Light Infantry on 22 October 1956 and [[Staff Captain]] Administration Branch at [[Army Headquarters, Colombo|Army Headquarters]] on 25 July 1958. He was transferred to the Corps of Infantry on 8 December 1962 and posted later to the [[Gemunu Watch]] on its formation. In December 1965, he was appointed [[Brigade Major]] of the 1st Brigade Group in [[Panagoda]]. From 23 February 1966 to 01 November 1967 he served as the Military Liaison Officer in the [[Ministry of External Affairs and Defence]]. He had followed the Unit Commander\u2019s Course in Australia.<ref name=\"GW1\"/>\n\n===Field command===\nOn 1 September 1968, he was appointed the acting [[Commanding Officer]] of the 1st Battalion of the Gemunu Watch. He was promoted to the rank of [[Lieutenant Colonel]] on 1 October 1969 and confirmed as the Commanding Officer. Later he took command of the [[Ceylon Army General Service Corps]] and the [[Ceylon Army Pioneer Corps]]. With the outbreak of the [[1971 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|1971 Insurrection]], he was appointed [[Military Coordinating Officer]] of the [[Monaragala District]] on 15 August 1971 and thereafter served as Military Coordinating Officer of the [[Kurunegala District]] from 16 April 1972 to 7 May 1972.<ref name=\"GW1\"/> \n\nOn 1 November 1972 he was appointed Commander, [[Task Force Anti Illicit Immigration]] (TAFII) in [[Jaffna]] serving till 1 March 1976, having been promoted to the rank of [[Colonel]] on 1 January 1974. On 1 March 1976, he was appointed Commander Western Command and later made Director Operations and Training at Army Headquarters on 15 September 1977. On 1 December 1977, he was promoted to the rank of [[Brigadier]] and appointed Inspector of Training of the Army. He had also served as Competent Authority for Sri Lanka Airports.<ref name=\"GW1\"/> \n\n===Higher command===\nOn 18 March 1979, he was appointed [[Chief of Staff]] of the Sri Lanka Army. Concurrently, Brigadier Weeratunga was then tasked by President [[J. R. Jayawardene]] to clamp down on the [[Sri Lankan Tamil militant groups|Tamil militancy]] that was taking root in [[Jaffna]] and was dispatched to Jaffna as Commander Security Forces - Jaffna, with extensive powers under the provisions of [[Prevention of Terrorism Act (Sri Lanka)|Prevention of Terrorism (Special Provisions) Act No: 48 of 1979]]. From 13 July 1979 to 31 December 1979, Brigadier Weeratunga lead extensive operations to route out the elements of Tamil militant groups forcing them to take refuge in India and reducing their terrorist activity.<ref>[http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=82009 ]</ref>   \n\nHe was promoted to the rank of [[Major General]] and made [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]] on 14 October 1981, and held the post till 2 November 1985. His tuner marked the start of the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]] with the [[LTTE]] ambush of the army patrol [[Four Four Bravo]] in July 1983. He undertook several reforms in the army, including the formation of the [[Gajaba Regiment]] and undertaking the rapid expansion of the army to cope with the civil war.<ref>[http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=82009 Gota survives blast at Mankulam, War on terror revisited]</ref>  \n\nHe was promoted to the rank of [[Lieutenant General]] and appointed as the first [[General Officer Commanding]] of the Joint Operation Command on 11 February 1985 to co-ordinate army, navy and air force [[counter-terrorist]] operations in the north and east of Sri Lanka. He retired from the army on 29 August 1986 and was promoted to the rank of [[General (Sri Lanka)|General]]. Brigadier [[Cyril Ranatunga]] was brought out of retirement with the rank of Lieutenant General to succeed General Weeratunga.<ref name=\"GW1\"/> \n\n==Later life==\nAfter leaving the army he was appointed Sri Lankan High Commissioner to Canada in October 1989 and served till 1990.<ref name=\"GW1\"/> He died at the age of 73 in November 2003 and was cremated with full Military Honours at General Cemetery Kanatte on November 9, 2003.<ref>[http://sundaytimes.lk/031109/front/ex.htm Ex -Army chief\u2019s funeral today]</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nHis decorations include the [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya]], [[Republic of Sri Lanka Armed Services Medal]], [[Ceylon Armed Services Long Service Medal]], [[Sri Lanka Armed Services Long Service Medal]] and [[Medal bar|Clasp]], [[Purna Bhumi Padakkama]], [[Ceylon Armed Services Inauguration Medal]], [[President's Inauguration Medal]] and the [[Sri Lanka Army 25th Anniversary Medal]].<ref name=\"GW1\"/> \n\n==Family==\nGeneral Weeratunga was married to Sonia Evangeline St.Clair Weeratunga ([[n\u00e9e]] Rhode) and had three children: Rohan, Annouchka and Ajith. The General\u2019s sister was Krishnajina Weeratunga who married Ana Seneviratne the Police IGP of the island nation. The family hailed from Galle and the family history was chronicalled by Sri Lankan Dutch  genealogist Gerard Cecil De Van Der Kroot of Cecil Lake Publications.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Sri Lankan Non Career Diplomats]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080505203152/http://www.army.lk/co.php www.army.lk]\n*[http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~lkawgw/gen3002.htm JAYEWARDENE, Don Adrian Wijesinghe (Tombi Mudaliyar) - Family #3002, rootsweb.ancestry.com]\n*[http://sundaytimes.lk/031109/columns/sitrep.html#1 Weeratunga: the man and his mission]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=Post created}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[General Officer Commanding|GOC]] of the Joint Operation Command|years=1985&ndash;1986}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Cyril Ranatunge]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Denis Perera]]}} \n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]]\n       |years=1981&ndash;1985}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nalin Seneviratne]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{succession box | title=Sri Lankan High Commissioners to Canada| before=? | after=? | years=1986&ndash;1990}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Commanders of the Sri Lankan Army}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weerathunga, T. I.}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan generals]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Royal College, Colombo]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Mons Officer Cadet School]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Joint Services Command and Staff College]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Sri Lanka Army]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese military personnel]]\n[[Category:Gemunu Watch officers]]\n[[Category:Sri Lanka Light Infantry officers]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of Sri Lanka to Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Tissa Indraka Weeratunga\n|birth_date=August 29, 1930\n|death_date=November 2003\n|birth_place= [[Matara, Sri Lanka|Matara]], [[Ceylon]]\n|death_place= [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]]\n|image=<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:General Tissa Weeratunga.jpg|250px]] -->\n|caption= General Tissa Weeratunga\n|nickname= Bull\n|allegiance= {{flagicon|Sri Lanka}} [[Sri Lanka]]\n|serviceyears= 1951-1986\n|rank=[[General]] \n|branch=[[Sri Lanka Army]]\n|commands=[[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|Chief of the Defence Staff]],<br>[[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]],<br> [[Chief of Staff]] of the Sri Lankan Army \n|unit=<!-- Commented out: [[File:SLLI Crest.gif|25px]] -->[[Ceylon Light Infantry]],<br>[[Gemunu Watch]]\n|battles= [[1971 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|1971 Insurrection]], <br>[[Sri Lankan Civil War]]\n|awards=[[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya]]\n|laterwork= [[High Commissioner (Commonwealth)|High Commissioner]] to [[Canada]]\n}}\n\n[[General (Sri Lanka)|General]] '''Tissa Indraka Weeratunga''', [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya|VSV]], [[National Defence College, India|ndc]], [[psc (British Army)|psc]], [[Gemunu Watch|GW]] (August 29, 1930 &ndash; November 2003) was a [[Sri Lanka]] [[general]]. He was a former [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]] (1981 \u2013 1985) and first [[General Officer Commanding]] (GOC) of the Joint Operations Headquarters (JOH) (at present referred [[Chief of the Defence Staff (Sri Lanka)|Chief of the Defence Staff]]), he was later Sri Lanka's [[High Commissioner (Commonwealth)|High Commissioner]] to Canada.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn to Arthur Weeratunga, [[Plantation|planter]] from [[Matara, Sri Lanka|Matara]] and Henrietta Weeratunga ([[n\u00e9e]] Gurusingha). He had one sister, Krishnajina who married [[Ana Seneviratne]] (former Sri Lankan Inspector-General of Police). Tissa Weeratunga was educated at the [[Royal College, Colombo]]. He was a graduate of the [[Joint Service Defence College]] and the [[National Defence College, India]].<ref name=\"GW1\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20150618042042/http://www.gemunuesra.lk/general_bull_weeratunga_remembered.html GENERAL TI WEERATHUNGA VSV ndc jssc (Retd) REMEMBERED]</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n===Early career===\nWeeratunga joined the newly formed Ceylon Army on 11 October 1949, in its first cadet officer intake and received his basic officer training at Mons Officer Cadet School, Aldershot and at [[Royal Military Academy, Sandhurst]], and was commissioned as a [[Second Lieutenant]] and posted to the [[Ceylon Light Infantry]] on 2 August 1951. He was appointed as [[adjutant]] of the [[Ruhunu Regiment]] on 4 July 1956; adjutant of the 1 Battalion, Ceylon Light Infantry on 22 October 1956 and [[Staff Captain]] Administration Branch at [[Army Headquarters, Colombo|Army Headquarters]] on 25 July 1958. He was transferred to the Corps of Infantry on 8 December 1962 and posted later to the [[Gemunu Watch]] on its formation. In December 1965, he was appointed [[Brigade Major]] of the 1st Brigade Group in [[Panagoda]]. From 23 February 1966 to 01 November 1967 he served as the Military Liaison Officer in the [[Ministry of External Affairs and Defence]]. He had followed the Unit Commander\u2019s Course in Australia.<ref name=\"GW1\"/>\n\n===Field command===\nOn 1 September 1968, he was appointed the acting [[Commanding Officer]] of the 1st Battalion of the Gemunu Watch. He was promoted to the rank of [[Lieutenant Colonel]] on 1 October 1969 and confirmed as the Commanding Officer. Later he took command of the [[Ceylon Army General Service Corps]] and the [[Ceylon Army Pioneer Corps]]. With the outbreak of the [[1971 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|1971 Insurrection]], he was appointed [[Military Coordinating Officer]] of the [[Monaragala District]] on 15 August 1971 and thereafter served as Military Coordinating Officer of the [[Kurunegala District]] from 16 April 1972 to 7 May 1972.<ref name=\"GW1\"/> \n\nOn 1 November 1972 he was appointed Commander, [[Task Force Anti Illicit Immigration]] (TAFII) in [[Jaffna]] serving till 1 March 1976, having been promoted to the rank of [[Colonel]] on 1 January 1974. On 1 March 1976, he was appointed Commander Western Command and later made Director Operations and Training at Army Headquarters on 15 September 1977. On 1 December 1977, he was promoted to the rank of [[Brigadier]] and appointed Inspector of Training of the Army. He had also served as Competent Authority for Sri Lanka Airports.<ref name=\"GW1\"/> \n\n===Higher command===\nOn 18 March 1979, he was appointed [[Chief of Staff]] of the Sri Lanka Army. Concurrently, Brigadier Weeratunga was then tasked by President [[J. R. Jayawardene]] to clamp down on the [[Sri Lankan Tamil militant groups|Tamil militancy]] that was taking root in [[Jaffna]] and was dispatched to Jaffna as Commander Security Forces - Jaffna, with extensive powers under the provisions of [[Prevention of Terrorism Act (Sri Lanka)|Prevention of Terrorism (Special Provisions) Act No: 48 of 1979]]. From 13 July 1979 to 31 December 1979, Brigadier Weeratunga lead extensive operations to route out the elements of Tamil militant groups forcing them to take refuge in India and reducing their terrorist activity.<ref>[http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=82009 ]</ref>   \n\nHe was promoted to the rank of [[Major General]] and made [[Commander of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Commander of the Sri Lankan Army]] on 14 October 1981, and held the post till 2 November 1985. His tuner marked the start of the [[Sri Lankan Civil War]] with the [[LTTE]] ambush of the army patrol [[Four Four Bravo]] in July 1983. He undertook several reforms in the army, including the formation of the [[Gajaba Regiment]] and undertaking the rapid expansion of the army to cope with the civil war.<ref>[http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=82009 Gota survives blast at Mankulam, War on terror revisited]</ref>  \n\nHe was promoted to the rank of [[Lieutenant General]] and appointed as the first [[General Officer Commanding]] of the Joint Operation Command on 11 February 1985 to co-ordinate army, navy and air force [[counter-terrorist]] operations in the north and east of Sri Lanka. He retired from the army on 29 August 1986 and was promoted to the rank of [[General (Sri Lanka)|General]]. Brigadier [[Cyril Ranatunga]] was brought out of retirement with the rank of Lieutenant General to succeed General Weeratunga.<ref name=\"GW1\"/> \n\n==Later life==\nAfter leaving the army he was appointed Sri Lankan High Commissioner to Canada in October 1989 and served till 1990.<ref name=\"GW1\"/> He died at the age of 73 in November 2003 and was cremated with full Military Honours at General Cemetery Kanatte on November 9, 2003.<ref>[http://sundaytimes.lk/031109/front/ex.htm Ex -Army chief\u2019s funeral today]</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nHis decorations include the [[Vishista Seva Vibhushanaya]], [[Republic of Sri Lanka Armed Services Medal]], [[Ceylon Armed Services Long Service Medal]], [[Sri Lanka Armed Services Long Service Medal]] and [[Medal bar|Clasp]], [[Purna Bhumi Padakkama]], [[Ceylon Armed Services Inauguration Medal]], [[President's Inauguration Medal]] and the [[Sri Lanka Army 25th Anniversary Medal]].<ref name=\"GW1\"/> \n\n==Family==\nGeneral Weeratunga was married to Sonia Evangeline St.Clair Weeratunga ([[n\u00e9e]] Rhode) and had three children: Rohan, Annouchka and Ajith. The General\u2019s sister was Krishnajina Weeratunga who married Ana Seneviratne the Police IGP of the island nation. The family hailed from Galle and the family history was chronicalled by Sri Lankan Dutch  genealogist Gerard Cecil De Van Der Kroot of Cecil Lake Publications.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Sri Lankan Non Career Diplomats]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080505203152/http://www.army.lk/co.php www.army.lk]\n*[http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~lkawgw/gen3002.htm JAYEWARDENE, Don Adrian Wijesinghe (Tombi Mudaliyar) - Family #3002, rootsweb.ancestry.com]\n*[http://sundaytimes.lk/031109/columns/sitrep.html#1 Weeratunga: the man and his mission]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=Post created}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[General Officer Commanding|GOC]] of the Joint Operation Command|ye